content:
This file defines the core types used within the DocMed repository.

## Key Exports

*   **`ManifestEntry`**: Represents an entry in the documentation manifest, including the file path, human-readable title, and a unique document key.
    ```typescript
    export type ManifestEntry = { filePath: string; title: string; docKey: string };
    ```
*   **`DocVersion`**: Represents a specific version of a document, including its timestamp, title, content, dependencies, and the Git commit ID.
    ```typescript
    export type DocVersion = {
      timestamp: string;
      title: string;
      content: string;
      dependencies: string[];
      commitId: string | null;
    };
    ```
*   **`DocFile`**: Represents a single documentation file, including its path, title, content, optional dependencies, and an array of its historical versions.
    ```typescript
    export type DocFile = {
      filePath: string;
      title: string;
      content: string;
      dependencies?: string[];
      versions?: DocVersion[];
    };
    ```
*   **`Commit`**: Represents a Git commit with its ID, message, pusher, and timestamp.
    ```typescript
    export type Commit = { id: string; message: string; pusher: string; timestamp: string };
    ```
*   **`DependencyGraph`**: A record where keys are document keys and values are arrays of document keys that the key document depends on.
    ```typescript
    export type DependencyGraph = Record<string, string[]>;
    ```
*   **`View`**: A discriminated union type representing the different possible views within the DocMed application (e.g., home, commits, dependency graph, specific document, folder).
    ```typescript
    export type View =
      | { type: "home" }
      | { type: "commits" }
      | { type: "deps"; focus?: string }
      | { type: "doc"; key: string }
      | { type: "folder"; path: string };
    ```
*   **`Tab`**: Represents a UI tab, containing a unique ID, the `View` it represents, and a human-readable label.
    ```typescript
    export type Tab = { id: string; view: View; label: string };
    ```

## Usage

These types are fundamental to the DocMed application, defining the structure of data handled throughout the project. For example, a `DocFile` might be used to store the parsed content of a Markdown file, while `View` types dictate how different sections of the application are navigated and rendered.
